# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-graph-viz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] In mathematics, and more specifically in graph theory, a **directed graph** (or **digraph**) is a graph that is made up of a set of vertices connected by directed edges, often called **arcs**.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] It differs from an ordinary or undirected graph, in that the latter is defined in terms of unordered pairs of vertices, which are usually called *edges*, *links* or *lines*.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] The aforementioned definition does not allow a directed graph to have multiple arrows with the same source and target nodes, but some authors consider a broader definition that allows directed graphs to have such multiple arcs (namely, they allow the arc set to be a multiset).
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] Sometimes these entities are called **directed multigraphs** (or **multidigraphs**).
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] On the other hand, the aforementioned definition allows a directed graph to have loops (that is, arcs that directly connect nodes with themselves), but some authors consider a narrower definition that does not allow directed graphs to have loops.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] Directed graphs without loops may be called **simple directed graphs**, while directed graphs with loops may be called *loop-digraphs* (see section Types of directed graph).
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] An arc (*x*, *y*) is considered to be directed *from* *x* *to* *y*; *y* is called the *head* and *x* is called the *tail* of the arc; *y* is said to be a *direct successor* of *x* and *x* is said to be a *direct predecessor* of *y*.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] If a path leads from *x* to *y*, then *y* is said to be a *successor* of *x* and *reachable* from *x*, and *x* is said to be a *predecessor* of *y*.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] The arc (*y*, *x*) is called the *reversed arc* of (*x*, *y*).
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a multidigraph with loops is the integer-valued matrix with rows and columns corresponding to the vertices, where a nondiagonal entry *a**ij* is the number of arcs from vertex *i* to vertex *j*, and the diagonal entry *a**ii* is the number of loops at vertex *i*.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph is a logical matrix, and is unique up to permutation of rows and columns.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] Another matrix representation for a directed graph is its incidence matrix.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] For a vertex, the number of head ends adjacent to a vertex is called the *indegree* of the vertex and the number of tail ends adjacent to a vertex is its *outdegree* (called *branching factor* in trees).
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] The indegree of *v* is denoted deg−(*v*) and its outdegree is denoted deg+(*v*).
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] A vertex with deg−(*v*) = 0 is called a *source*, as it is the origin of each of its outgoing arcs.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] Similarly, a vertex with deg+(*v*) = 0 is called a *sink*, since it is the end of each of its incoming arcs.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] If for every vertex *v* ∈ *V*, deg+(*v*) = deg−(*v*), the graph is called a *balanced directed graph*.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] The degree sequence of a directed graph is the list of its indegree and outdegree pairs; for the above example we have degree sequence ((2, 0), (2, 2), (0, 2), (1, 1)).
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] The degree sequence is a directed graph invariant so isomorphic directed graphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] However, the degree sequence does not, in general, uniquely identify a directed graph; in some cases, non-isomorphic digraphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] The directed graph realization problem is the problem of finding a directed graph with the degree sequence a given sequence of positive integer pairs.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] This problem can either be solved by the Kleitman–Wang algorithm or by the Fulkerson–Chen–Anstee theorem.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] A directed graph is *weakly connected* (or just *connected*) if the undirected *underlying graph* obtained by replacing all directed edges of the graph with undirected edges is a connected graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] A directed graph is *strongly connected* or *strong* if it contains a directed path from *x* to *y* (and from *y* to *x*) for every pair of vertices (*x*, *y*).
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] The *strong components* are the maximal strongly connected subgraphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/directed-graph] A connected rooted graph (or *flow graph*) is one where there exists a directed path to every vertex from a distinguished *root vertex*.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] In computer science, a **graph** is an abstract data type that is meant to implement the undirected graph and directed graph concepts from the field of graph theory within mathematics.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure consists of a finite (and possibly mutable) set of *vertices* (also called *nodes* or *points*), together with a set of unordered pairs of these vertices for an undirected graph or a set of ordered pairs for a directed graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] These pairs are known as *edges* (also called *links* or *lines*), and for a directed graph are also known as *edges* but also sometimes *arrows* or *arcs*.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertices may be part of the graph structure, or may be external entities represented by integer indices or references.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] A graph data structure may also associate to each edge some *edge value*, such as a symbolic label or a numeric attribute (cost, capacity, length, etc.).
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] This data structure allows the storage of additional data on the vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Additional data can be stored if edges are also stored as objects, in which case each vertex stores its incident edges and each edge stores its incident vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent source vertices and columns represent destination vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Data on edges and vertices must be stored externally.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Only the cost for one edge can be stored between each pair of vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] A two-dimensional matrix, in which the rows represent the vertices and columns represent the edges.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] The entries indicate the incidence relation between the vertex at a row and edge at a column.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] The following table gives the time complexity cost of performing various operations on graphs, for each of these representations, with |*V*| the number of vertices and |*E*| the number of edges.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] In the matrix representations, the entries encode the cost of following an edge.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] The cost of edges that are not present are assumed to be ∞.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] A representation of adjacent vertices via hash tables leads to an amortized average time complexity of $O(1)$ to test adjacency of two given vertices and to remove an edge and an amortized average time complexity of $O(\deg(x))$ to remove a given vertex x of degree $\deg(x)$ .
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] The time complexity of the other operations and the asymptotic space requirement do not change.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] The parallelization of graph problems faces significant challenges: Data-driven computations, unstructured problems, poor locality and high data access to computation ratio.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] The graph representation used for parallel architectures plays a significant role in facing those challenges.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Poorly chosen representations may unnecessarily drive up the communication cost of the algorithm, which will decrease its scalability.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] In the following, shared and distributed memory architectures are considered.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] In the case of a shared memory model, the graph representations used for parallel processing are the same as in the sequential case, since parallel read-only access to the graph representation (e.g. an adjacency list) is efficient in shared memory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] In the distributed memory model, the usual approach is to partition the vertex set V of the graph into p sets $V_{0},\dots ,V_{p-1}$ .
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Here, p is the amount of available processing elements (PE).
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] The vertex set partitions are then distributed to the PEs with matching index, additionally to the corresponding edges.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Every PE has its own subgraph representation, where edges with an endpoint in another partition require special attention.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] For standard communication interfaces like MPI, the ID of the PE owning the other endpoint has to be identifiable.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] During computation in a distributed graph algorithms, passing information along these edges implies communication.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Partitioning the graph needs to be done carefully - there is a trade-off between low communication and even size partitioning But partitioning a graph is a NP-hard problem, so it is not feasible to calculate them.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Instead, the following heuristics are used.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] 1D partitioning: Every processor gets $n/p$ vertices and the corresponding outgoing edges.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be understood as a row-wise or column-wise decomposition of the adjacency matrix.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] For algorithms operating on this representation, this requires an All-to-All communication step as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ message buffer sizes, as each PE potentially has outgoing edges to every other PE.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] 2D partitioning: Every processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Assume the processors are aligned in a rectangle $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ , where $p_{r}$ and $p_{c}$ are the amount of processing elements in each row and column, respectively.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Then each processor gets a submatrix of the adjacency matrix of dimension $(n/p_{r})\times (n/p_{c})$ .
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be visualized as a checkerboard pattern in a matrix.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Therefore, each processing unit can only have outgoing edges to PEs in the same row and column.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] This bounds the amount of communication partners for each PE to $p_{r}+p_{c}-1$ out of $p=p_{r}\times p_{c}$ possible ones.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Graphs with trillions of edges occur in machine learning, social network analysis, and other areas.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Compressed graph representations have been developed to reduce I/O and memory requirements.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] General techniques such as Huffman coding are applicable, but the adjacency list or adjacency matrix can be processed in specific ways to increase efficiency.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Breadth-first search (BFS) and depth-first search (DFS) are two closely related approaches that are used for exploring all of the nodes in a given connected component.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Both start with an arbitrary node, the "root".
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Strongly connected components can also be found using graph traversals using algorithms such as Kosaraju's algorithm, which is a modified DFS.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] Dijkstra's Algorithm is a Pathfinding Algorithm that can be used on a positively-weighted (meaning all edge weights must be greater than or equal to 0) and/or directed graphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-abstract-data-type] This can be used to find the shortest path between two arbitrarily chosen nodes which is commonly applied in routing problems.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] A drawing of a graph or **network diagram** is a pictorial representation of the vertices and edges of a graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] This drawing should not be confused with the graph itself: very different layouts can correspond to the same graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] In the abstract, all that matters is which pairs of vertices are connected by edges.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] In the concrete, however, the arrangement of these vertices and edges within a drawing affects its understandability, usability, fabrication cost, and aesthetics.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] The problem gets worse if the graph changes over time by adding and deleting edges (dynamic graph drawing) and the goal is to preserve the user's mental map.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] Graphs are frequently drawn as node–link diagrams in which the vertices are represented as disks, boxes, or textual labels and the edges are represented as line segments, polylines, or curves in the Euclidean plane.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] Node–link diagrams can be traced back to the 14th-16th century works of Pseudo-Lull which were published under the name of Ramon Llull, a 13th century polymath.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] Pseudo-Lull drew diagrams of this type for complete graphs in order to analyze all pairwise combinations among sets of metaphysical concepts.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] In the case of directed graphs, arrowheads form a commonly used graphical convention to show their orientation; however, user studies have shown that other conventions such as tapering provide this information more effectively.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] Upward planar drawing uses the convention that every edge is oriented from a lower vertex to a higher vertex, making arrowheads unnecessary.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] Many different quality measures have been defined for graph drawings, in an attempt to find objective means of evaluating their aesthetics and usability.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] In addition to guiding the choice between different layout methods for the same graph, some layout methods attempt to directly optimize these measures.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] In addition, the placement and routing steps of electronic design automation (EDA) are similar in many ways to graph drawing, as is the problem of greedy embedding in distributed computing, and the graph drawing literature includes several results borrowed from the EDA literature.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-drawing] There are many algorithms for graph drawing.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In mathematics and computer science, **graph theory** is the study of graphs, which are mathematical structures used to model pairwise relations between objects.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A graph in this context is made up of vertices (also called nodes or points) which are connected by edges (also called arcs, links, or lines).
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A distinction is made between undirected graphs, where edges link two vertices symmetrically, and directed graphs, where edges link two vertices asymmetrically.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graphs are one of the principal objects of study in discrete mathematics.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory is a branch of mathematics that studies graphs, mathematical structures for modelling pairwise relations between objects.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] It is part of discrete mathematics, often considered part of combinatorics, although it is a stand-alone field due to its great growth and distinct from other fields, having its own kind of problems.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The term "graph" was introduced by James Joseph Sylvester in a paper published in 1878 in *Nature*, where he drew an analogy between "quantic invariants" and "co-variants" of algebra and molecular diagrams.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The definition of a graph can vary, but one can understand that a graph is a structure consisting of vertices (also called nodes or points) and edges (also called arcs, links, or lines).
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Two vertices of an edge are called the endpoints.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Occasionally, a graph is called an undirected graph, to distinguish it from a directed graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A directed graph is a graph where each edge has an assignment direction known as orientation, designated with an arrow.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A mixed graph can have edges that may be directed, and some may be undirected.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A graph can also be called a simple graph, to distinguish it from a multigraph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A multigraph allows many edges to have the same pair of endpoints, and it also allows an edge to connect a vertex to itself, known as a loop.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A graph can have its edges assigned a number, which is known as the weight.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Such a graph is called a weighted graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In 1736, Leonhard Euler published a paper titled *Solutio Problematis ad Geometriam Situs Pertinentis* on the Seven Bridges of Königsberg, which is regarded as the first paper in the history of graph theory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Euler's paper and Alexandre-Théophile Vandermonde's 1771 *Remarques sur les Problèmes de Situation* paper on the knight's tour carried on with the *analysis situs*, initiated by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Euler's characteristic relating the number of edges, vertices, and faces of a convex polyhedron was studied and generalized by Augustin-Louis Cauchy and Simon Antoine Jean L'Huilier, and represents the beginning of the branch of mathematics known as topology.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] More than one century after Euler's paper on the bridges of Königsberg, and while Johann Benedict Listing was introducing the concept of topology, Arthur Cayley was led by an interest in particular analytical forms arising from differential calculus to study a particular class of graphs, the trees.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This study had many implications for theoretical chemistry.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The techniques he used mainly concern the enumeration of graphs with particular properties.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Enumerative graph theory then arose from the results of Cayley and the fundamental results published by Pólya between 1935 and 1937.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] These were generalized by Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn in 1959.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Cayley linked his results on trees with contemporary studies of chemical composition.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The fusion of ideas from mathematics with those from chemistry began what has become part of the standard terminology of graph theory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The autonomous development of topology from 1860 to 1930 fertilized graph theory back through the works of Camille Jordan, Kazimierz Kuratowski, and Hassler Whitney.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Another important factor in the common development of graph theory and topology came from the use of the techniques of modern algebra.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The first example of such a use comes from the work of the physicist Gustav Kirchhoff, who published in 1845 his Kirchhoff's circuit laws for calculating the voltage and current in electric circuits.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The first textbook on graph theory was written by Dénes Kőnig, and published in 1936.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Another book by Frank Harary, published in 1969, was "considered the world over to be the definitive textbook on the subject", and enabled mathematicians, chemists, electrical engineers and social scientists to talk to each other.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Harary donated all of the royalties to fund the Pólya Prize.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] One of the most famous problems in graph theory is the four color problem: Is it true that any map drawn in the plane may have its regions colored with four colors, in such a way that any two regions having a common border have different colors?
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This problem was first posed by Francis Guthrie in 1852, and its first written record is in a letter of Augustus De Morgan addressed to William Rowan Hamilton the same year.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Many incorrect proofs have been proposed, including those by Augustin Cayley, Alfred Kempe, and others.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The study and the generalization of this problem by Peter Tait, Percy John Heawood, Frank P.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Ramsey and Hadwiger led to the study of the colorings of the graphs embedded on surfaces with arbitrary genus.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Tait's reformulation generated a new class of problems, the *factorization problems*, particularly studied by Petersen and Dénes Kőnig.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The works of Ramsey on colorations, and more specially, the results obtained by Pál Turán in 1941, were at the origin of another branch of graph theory, known as extremal graph theory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The four-color problem remained unsolved for more than a century.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In 1969, Heinrich Heesch published a method for solving the problem using computers.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A computer-aided proof produced in 1976 by Kenneth Appel and Wolfgang Haken makes fundamental use of the notion of "discharging" developed by Heesch.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The proof involved checking the properties of 1,936 configurations by computer, and was not fully accepted at the time due to its complexity.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A simpler proof considering only 633 configurations was given twenty years later by Robertson, Seymour, Sanders and Thomas.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The introduction of probabilistic methods in graph theory, especially in the study of Erdős and Rényi of the asymptotic probability of graph connectivity, gave rise to yet another branch, known as random graph theory, which has been a fruitful source of graph-theoretic results.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Topological graph theory deals with the study of graphs related to topology.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Topological graph theory deals with the study of graphs as topological spaces.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The graph in a topology is a set of simplexes that is called the simplicial one-dimensional complex.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This subarea studies the embedding (or imbedding) of a graph in surface and linkless embedding, graph minors, crossing number, map coloring, and voltage graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The embedding of a graph in a surface is the representation of a graph in which the points are associated with the vertices and simple arcs with edges in a surface.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The endpoints are associated with an edge, and the points with the end vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] No arcs include points associated with other vertices, and two arcs never intersect at a point that is interior to either of the arcs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The graph embedding can be generalized into the linkless embedding, whereby no two cycles of the graph are linked in three-dimensional Euclidean space, and a book, a collection of half-planes all having the same line as their boundary.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The graph is said to be minor if it can be formed from another graph by deleting vertices and edges, and by edge-contraction.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The earliest result of the graph minor theory is from Wagner's theorem, stating that a finite graph is planar if and only if its minor includes neither the complete graph on five vertices $K_{5}$ nor the utility graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A related result is the Robertson–Seymour theorem, implying the existence of forbidden minor for every property of graphs preserved by deletions and edge contractions.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The crossing number tells the minimum number of crossing edges of a graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This study originated from a Hungarian mathematician Pál Turán who asked for a factory plan that minimized the number of crossings between tracks connecting brick kilns to storage sites.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This problem can be formalized as asking for the crossing number of a complete bipartite graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A graph coloring is a methodical assignment of labelling the elements of a graph, which is traditionally called colors.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In coloring, no two adjacent elements have the same color.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] It requires the minimum number of colors, which is known as the chromatic number.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Four-color theorem stated that no more than four colors are required to color the regions of any map so that no two adjacent regions have the same color; that is, no two regions share a common boundary.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This theorem is stronger than five-color theorem.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Relatedly, Earth–Moon problem is known for the nowadays open problem on extension of the planar map coloring problem, solved by the four-color theorem.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A voltage graph is a directed graph whose edges are labelled invertibly by elements of a group.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This graph concisely specifies the derived graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] It is also a common way to form a covering graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Algebraic graph theory is the study of graph theory that involves major branches of algebra.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Major branches of algebra that are used are linear algebra and group theory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A study of graph theory using linear algebra is called spectral graph theory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This study focuses on adjacency matrix, a matrix that represents the graph, and its spectrum, which focuses on the characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors of the given adjacency matrix.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] It also focuses on the Laplacian matrix of a graph, which involves the degree matrix (a diagonal matrix that represents the degree of a vertex) and the adjacency matrix.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Group theory, particularly automorphism groups and geometric group theory, focuses on various families of graphs based on symmetry in algebraic graph theory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Such a symmetry includes symmetric graphs, vertex-transitive graphs, edge-transitive graphs, distance-transitive graphs, distance-regular graphs, and strongly regular graphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Frucht's theorem states that every finite group is the group of symmetries of a finite undirected graph, or more strongly, there exist infinitely many non-isomorphic simple connected graphs such that the automorphism group of each of them is isomorphic to a finite group.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Algebraic graph theory also studies the algebraic invariants, chromatic polynomial, Tutte polynomial of a graph, and knot invariant.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A graph invariant is a property of graphs that depends only on the abstract structure, instead of labellings or drawings of the graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A chromatic polynomial is a polynomial that counts the number of graph colorings as a function of the number of colors.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The Tutte polynomial is a two-variable polynomial on graph connectivity.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Geometric graph theory studies a graph drawn with straight-line or continuous curved edges with geometric properties combinatorially.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Geometric graph theory focuses on combinatorial and geometric properties of a graph that is drawn in a plane with straight-line or continuous curved edges in Euclidean space.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] As part of discrete geometry and computational geometry, geometric graph theory studies planar graphs, relationship to higher-dimensional convex polytopes, intersection of geometrical shaped sets, and other geometries' subareas of incidence geometry and projective geometry.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A planar graph wherein its vertices are embedded as points, and its edges are non-crossing line segments in the Euclidean plane is called planar straight-line graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Any planar graph can be represented as a planar straight-line graph by Fáry's theorem.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The planar straight-line graph is the special case of a Euclidean graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The Euclidean graph allows its edges to have the length of the Euclidean distance between its endpoints.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A visibility graph is a graph whose vertices and edges are the point locations and visible connections, respectively.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In a simple polygon, where its edges are not self-intersecting and have no holes, the vertices of a visibility graph are connected by edges that represent the sides and diagonals of a polygon.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The vertices are defined as the point locations.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Polyhedral graph is an undirected graph that forms the vertices and edges of a three-dimensional convex polyhedron.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In order to achieve it, such a graph must meet the requirements of Steinitz's theorem, stating that every convex polyhedron is 3-vertex connected planar graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The planar graph remains connected whenever any two of its vertices are removed.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] An intersection graph is a graph in which each vertex is associated with a set and in which vertices are connected by edges whenever the corresponding sets have a nonempty intersection.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Each vertex is represented as a set, and every two vertices are connected.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Hence, the intersection graph of finite sets can be represented through the smallest number of required elements, known as the intersection number.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The result graph can be geometric whenever the sets are geometrical objects.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] For instance, the intersection graph of line segments in one dimension is an interval graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The intersection graph of unit disks in the plane is a unit disk graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The intersection of a circle packing is a coin graph, where a vertex and an edge represent a circle and every pair of tangent circles; by Koebe–Andreev–Thurston theorem, the intersection graphs of non-crossing circles are exactly the planar graphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Scheinerman's theorem states that every planar graph can be represented as the intersection graph of line segments in the plane.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The Levi graph is a bipartite graph that associates to the incidence structure and projective configuration.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] By applying to information visualization, this creates another subarea of graph theory that is known as graph drawing, which visualizes a graph depiction.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Frequently drawn as node–link diagrams, the vertices of a graph are represented as disks, boxes, or textual labels, and the edges are represented as line segments, polylines, or curves in the Euclidean plane.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Many definitions for graph drawings based on quality measures include the crossing number, area, symmetry display on finding the problem of a graph's group automorphism, bend minimization, angular resolution, and slope number.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Tools for graph drawings are the circle packing, the intersection graph, and other visualizations of the adjacency matrix.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Extremal graph theory is a branch of mathematics at the intersection of extremal combinatorics and graph theory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This area studies the maximum number of a graph's edges, known as the extremal number.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The subarea's milestone originated from Mantel's theorem on the extremal number of a triangle-free graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Turán's theorem extended Mantel's theorem for any undirected graph that does not have a complete subgraph of a given size.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Turán's theorem is generalized by Erdős–Stone theorem, which is occasionally known as the "fundamental theorem of extremal graph theory".
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Extremal graph theory also studies forbidden subgraph problem, homomorphism density, and Szemerédi regularity lemma.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The forbidden subgraphs problem suggests finding the extremal number of a graph with n vertices such that it does not have a subgraph that is isomorphic to the graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A homomorphism density is a parameter that involves the graph homomorphism.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The density may refer to the probability that a map from the vertices of a graph to the vertices of another one chosen uniformly at random is a graph homomorphism.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Being homomorphic means there exists a mapping between two graphs that respects their structure, or equivalently, a function between the vertex sets of two graphs that maps adjacent vertices to adjacent vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Szemerédi's regularity lemma states that a graph can be partitioned into a bounded number of parts so that the edges between parts are $\varepsilon$ -regular.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The theory of random graph focuses on graphs using probabilistic method.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The subarea was founded by Hungarian mathematicians Paul Erdős and Alfréd Rényi, whose modelling generates random graphs, known as Erdős–Rényi model.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A tree is an undirected graph where every pair of vertices is connected by exactly one path.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Therefore, a random tree is a tree that is formed by a stochastic process.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graphs can be used to model many types of relations and processes in physical, biological, social and information systems.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Many practical problems can be represented by graphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Emphasizing their application to real-world systems, the term *network* is sometimes defined to mean a graph in which attributes (e.g. names) are associated with the vertices and edges, and the subject that expresses and understands real-world systems as a network is called network science.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Within computer science, 'causal' and 'non-causal' linked structures are graphs that are used to represent networks of communication, data organization, computational devices, the flow of computation, etc.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] For instance, the link structure of a website can be represented by a directed graph, in which the vertices (nodes) represent web pages and directed edges represent links from one page to another.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A similar approach can be taken to problems in social media, travel, biology, computer chip design, mapping the progression of neuro-degenerative diseases, and many other fields.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The development of algorithms to handle graphs is therefore of major interest in computer science.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The transformation of graphs is often formalized and represented by graph rewrite systems.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Complementary to graph transformation systems focusing on rule-based in-memory manipulation of graphs are graph databases geared towards transaction-safe, persistent storing and querying of graph-structured data.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graph-theoretic methods, in various forms, have proven particularly useful in linguistics, since natural language often lends itself well to discrete structure.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Traditionally, syntax and compositional semantics follow tree-based structures, whose expressive power lies in the principle of compositionality, modeled in a hierarchical graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] More contemporary approaches such as head-driven phrase structure grammar model the syntax of natural language using typed feature structures, which are directed acyclic graphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Within lexical semantics, especially as applied to computers, modeling word meaning is easier when a given word is understood in terms of related words; semantic networks are therefore important in computational linguistics.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Still, other methods in phonology (e.g. optimality theory, which uses lattice graphs) and morphology (e.g. finite-state morphology, using finite-state transducers) are common in the analysis of language as a graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Indeed, the usefulness of this area of mathematics to linguistics has borne organizations such as TextGraphs, as well as various 'Net' projects, such as WordNet, VerbNet, and others.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory is also used to study molecules in chemistry and physics.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In condensed matter physics, the three-dimensional structure of complicated simulated atomic structures can be studied quantitatively by gathering statistics on graph-theoretic properties related to the topology of the atoms.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Also, "the Feynman graphs and rules of calculation summarize quantum field theory in a form in close contact with the experimental numbers one wants to understand." In chemistry a graph makes a natural model for a molecule, where vertices represent atoms and edges bonds.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This approach is especially used in computer processing of molecular structures, ranging from chemical editors to database searching.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In statistical physics, graphs can represent local connections between interacting parts of a system, as well as the dynamics of a physical process on such systems.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Similarly, in computational neuroscience graphs can be used to represent functional connections between brain areas that interact to give rise to various cognitive processes, where the vertices represent different areas of the brain and the edges represent the connections between those areas.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory plays an important role in electrical modeling of electrical networks, here, weights are associated with resistance of the wire segments to obtain electrical properties of network structures.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graphs are also used to represent the micro-scale channels of porous media, in which the vertices represent the pores and the edges represent the smaller channels connecting the pores.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Chemical graph theory uses the molecular graph as a means to model molecules.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graphs and networks are excellent models to study and understand phase transitions and critical phenomena.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Removal of nodes or edges leads to a critical transition where the network breaks into small clusters which is studied as a phase transition.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This breakdown is studied via percolation theory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory is also widely used in sociology as a way, for example, to measure actors' prestige or to explore rumor spreading, notably through the use of social network analysis software.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Under the umbrella of social networks are many different types of graphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Acquaintanceship and friendship graphs describe whether people know each other.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Influence graphs model whether certain people can influence the behavior of others.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Finally, collaboration graphs model whether two people work together in a particular way, such as acting in a movie together.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Likewise, graph theory is useful in biology and conservation efforts where a vertex can represent regions where certain species exist (or inhabit) and the edges represent migration paths or movement between the regions.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] This information is important when looking at breeding patterns or tracking the spread of disease, parasites or how changes to the movement can affect other species.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graphs are also commonly used in molecular biology and genomics to model and analyze datasets with complex relationships.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] For example, graph-based methods are often used to 'cluster' cells together into cell-types in single-cell transcriptome analysis.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Another use is to model genes or proteins in a pathway and study the relationships between them, such as metabolic pathways and gene regulatory networks.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Evolutionary trees, ecological networks, and hierarchical clustering of gene expression patterns are also represented as graph structures.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory is also used in connectomics; nervous systems can be seen as a graph, where the nodes are neurons and the edges are the connections between them.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A graph structure can be extended by assigning a weight to each edge of the graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graphs with weights, or weighted graphs, are used to represent structures in which pairwise connections have some numerical values.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] For example, if a graph represents a road network, the weights could represent the length of each road.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] There may be several weights associated with each edge, including distance (as in the previous example), travel time, or monetary cost.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Such weighted graphs are commonly used to program GPS's, and travel-planning search engines that compare flight times and costs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A graph is an abstraction of relationships that emerge in nature; hence, it cannot be coupled to a certain representation.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The way it is represented depends on the degree of convenience such representation provides for a certain application.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The most common representations are the visual, in which, usually, vertices are drawn and connected by edges, and the tabular, in which rows of a table provide information about the relationships between the vertices within the graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graphs are usually represented visually by drawing a point or circle for every vertex, and drawing a line between two vertices if they are connected by an edge.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] If the graph is directed, the direction is indicated by drawing an arrow.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] If the graph is weighted, the weight is added on the arrow.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A graph drawing should not be confused with the graph itself (the abstract, non-visual structure) as there are several ways to structure the graph drawing.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] All that matters is which vertices are connected to which others by how many edges and not the exact layout.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In practice, it is often difficult to decide if two drawings represent the same graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Depending on the problem domain some layouts may be better suited and easier to understand than others.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Tutte was very influential on the subject of graph drawing.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Among other achievements, he introduced the use of linear algebraic methods to obtain graph drawings.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Graph drawing also can be said to encompass problems that deal with the crossing number and its various generalizations.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The crossing number of a graph is the minimum number of intersections between edges that a drawing of the graph in the plane must contain.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] For a planar graph, the crossing number is zero by definition.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Drawings on surfaces other than the plane are also studied.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] There are other techniques to visualize a graph away from vertices and edges, including circle packings, intersection graph, and other visualizations of the adjacency matrix.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The tabular representation lends itself well to computational applications.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] There are different ways to store graphs in a computer system.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The data structure used depends on both the graph structure and the algorithm used for manipulating the graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Theoretically one can distinguish between list and matrix structures but in concrete applications the best structure is often a combination of both.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] List structures are often preferred for sparse graphs as they have smaller memory requirements.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Matrix structures on the other hand provide faster access for some applications but can consume huge amounts of memory.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Implementations of sparse matrix structures that are efficient on modern parallel computer architectures are an object of current investigation.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] List structures include the edge list, an array of pairs of vertices, and the adjacency list, which separately lists the neighbors of each vertex: Much like the edge list, each vertex has a list of which vertices it is adjacent to.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Matrix structures include the incidence matrix, a matrix of 0's and 1's whose rows represent vertices and whose columns represent edges, and the adjacency matrix, in which both the rows and columns are indexed by vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In both cases a 1 indicates two adjacent objects and a 0 indicates two non-adjacent objects.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The degree matrix indicates the degree of vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The Laplacian matrix is a modified form of the adjacency matrix that incorporates information about the degrees of the vertices, and is useful in some calculations such as Kirchhoff's theorem on the number of spanning trees of a graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The distance matrix, like the adjacency matrix, has both its rows and columns indexed by vertices, but rather than containing a 0 or a 1 in each cell it contains the length of a shortest path between two vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] There is a large literature on graphical enumeration: the problem of counting graphs meeting specified conditions.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Some of this work is found in Harary and Palmer (1973).
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A common problem, called the subgraph isomorphism problem, is finding a fixed graph as a subgraph in a given graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] One reason to be interested in such a question is that many graph properties are *hereditary* for subgraphs, which means that a graph has the property if and only if all subgraphs have it too.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Finding maximal subgraphs of a certain kind is often an NP-complete problem.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] One special case of subgraph isomorphism is the graph isomorphism problem.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] It asks whether two graphs are isomorphic.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] It is not known whether this problem is NP-complete, nor whether it can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A similar problem is finding induced subgraphs in a given graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Again, some important graph properties are hereditary with respect to induced subgraphs, which means that a graph has a property if and only if all induced subgraphs also have it.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Finding maximal induced subgraphs of a certain kind is also often NP-complete.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Still another such problem, the minor containment problem, is to find a fixed graph as a minor of a given graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A minor or subcontraction of a graph is any graph obtained by taking a subgraph and contracting some (or no) edges.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Many graph properties are hereditary for minors, which means that a graph has a property if and only if all minors have it too.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A similar problem, the subdivision containment problem, is to find a fixed graph as a subdivision of a given graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] A subdivision or homeomorphism of a graph is any graph obtained by subdividing some (or no) edges.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Subdivision containment is related to graph properties such as planarity.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Another class of problems has to do with the extent to which various species and generalizations of graphs are determined by their *point-deleted subgraphs*.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Many problems and theorems in graph theory have to do with various ways of coloring graphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Typically, one is interested in coloring a graph so that no two adjacent vertices have the same color, or with other similar restrictions.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] One may also consider coloring edges (possibly so that no two coincident edges are the same color), or other variations.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Constraint modeling theories concern families of directed graphs related by a partial order.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] In these applications, graphs are ordered by specificity, meaning that more constrained graphs—which are more specific and thus contain a greater amount of information—are subsumed by those that are more general.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Operations between graphs include evaluating the direction of a subsumption relationship between two graphs, if any, and computing graph unification.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] The unification of two argument graphs is defined as the most general graph (or the computation thereof) that is consistent with (i.e. contains all of the information in) the inputs, if such a graph exists; efficient unification algorithms are known.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] For constraint frameworks which are strictly compositional, graph unification is the sufficient satisfiability and combination function.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Well-known applications include automatic theorem proving and modeling the elaboration of linguistic structure.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Covering problems in graphs may refer to various set cover problems on subsets of vertices/subgraphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Decomposition, defined as partitioning the edge set of a graph (with as many vertices as necessary accompanying the edges of each part of the partition), has a wide variety of questions.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Often, the problem is to decompose a graph into subgraphs isomorphic to a fixed graph; for instance, decomposing a complete graph into Hamiltonian cycles.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Other problems specify a family of graphs into which a given graph should be decomposed, for instance, a family of cycles, or decomposing a complete graph *K**n* into *n* − 1 specified trees having, respectively, 1, 2, 3, ..., *n* − 1 edges.
[src:network-graph-viz/graph-theory] Many problems involve characterizing the members of various classes of graphs.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] An **influence diagram** (**ID**) (also called a **relevance diagram**, **decision diagram** or a **decision network**) is a compact graphical and mathematical representation of a decision situation.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] It is a generalization of a Bayesian network, in which not only probabilistic inference problems but also decision making problems (following the maximum expected utility criterion) can be modeled and solved.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] ID was first developed in the mid-1970s by decision analysts with an intuitive semantic that is easy to understand.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] It is now adopted widely and becoming an alternative to the decision tree which typically suffers from exponential growth in number of branches with each variable modeled.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] ID is directly applicable in team decision analysis, since it allows incomplete sharing of information among team members to be modeled and solved explicitly.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] Extensions of ID also find their use in game theory as an alternative representation of the game tree.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] An ID is a directed acyclic graph with three types (plus one subtype) of node and three types of arc (or arrow) between nodes.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] Formally, the semantic of influence diagram is based on sequential construction of nodes and arcs, which implies a specification of all conditional independencies in the diagram.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] The specification is defined by the d -separation criterion of Bayesian network.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] According to this semantic, every node is probabilistically independent on its non-successor nodes given the outcome of its immediate predecessor nodes.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] Likewise, a missing arc between non-value node X and non-value node Y implies that there exists a set of non-value nodes Z , e.g., the parents of Y , that renders Y independent of X given the outcome of the nodes in Z .
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] Consider the simple influence diagram representing a situation where a decision-maker is planning their vacation.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] The above example highlights the power of the influence diagram in representing an extremely important concept in decision analysis known as the value of information.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] Scenario 1 is the best possible scenario for this decision situation since there is no longer any uncertainty on what they care about (*Weather Condition*) when making their decision.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] Scenario 3, however, is the worst possible scenario for this decision situation since they need to make their decision without any hint (*Weather Forecast*) on what they care about (*Weather Condition*) will turn out to be.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] The decision-maker is usually better off (definitely no worse off, on average) to move from scenario 3 to scenario 2 through the acquisition of new information.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] The most they should be willing to pay for such move is called the value of information on *Weather Forecast*, which is essentially the value of imperfect information on *Weather Condition*.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] The applicability of this simple ID and the value of information concept is tremendous, especially in medical decision making when most decisions have to be made with imperfect information about their patients, diseases, etc.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] Influence diagrams are hierarchical and can be defined either in terms of their structure or in greater detail in terms of the functional and numerical relation between diagram elements.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] An ID that is consistently defined at all levels—structure, function, and number—is a well-defined mathematical representation and is referred to as a *well-formed influence diagram* (WFID).
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] WFIDs can be evaluated using reversal and removal operations to yield answers to a large class of probabilistic, inferential, and decision questions.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] More recent techniques have been developed by artificial intelligence researchers concerning Bayesian network inference (belief propagation).
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] An influence diagram having only uncertainty nodes (i.e., a Bayesian network) is also called a **relevance diagram**.
[src:network-graph-viz/influence-diagram] An arc connecting node *A* to *B* implies not only that "*A* is relevant to *B*", but also that "*B* is relevant to *A*" (i.e., relevance is a symmetric relationship).
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] In a diagram of a graph, a vertex is usually represented by a circle with a label, and an edge is represented by a line or arrow extending from one vertex to another.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] The two vertices forming an edge are said to be the endpoints of this edge, and the edge is said to be incident to the vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] A vertex *w* is said to be adjacent to another vertex *v* if the graph contains an edge (*v*,*w*).
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] The neighborhood of a vertex *v* is an induced subgraph of the graph, formed by all vertices adjacent to *v*.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] The degree of a vertex, denoted 𝛿(v) in a graph is the number of edges incident to it.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] An **isolated vertex** is a vertex with degree zero; that is, a vertex that is not an endpoint of any edge (the example image illustrates one isolated vertex).
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] A **leaf vertex** (also **pendant vertex**) is a vertex with degree one.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] In a directed graph, one can distinguish the outdegree (number of outgoing edges), denoted 𝛿 +(v), from the indegree (number of incoming edges), denoted 𝛿−(v); a **source vertex** is a vertex with indegree zero, while a **sink vertex** is a vertex with outdegree zero.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] A simplicial vertex is one whose closed neighborhood forms a clique: every two neighbors are adjacent.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] A universal vertex is a vertex that is adjacent to every other vertex in the graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] A cut vertex is a vertex the removal of which would disconnect the remaining graph; a vertex separator is a collection of vertices the removal of which would disconnect the remaining graph into small pieces.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] A k-vertex-connected graph is a graph in which removing fewer than *k* vertices always leaves the remaining graph connected.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] An independent set is a set of vertices no two of which are adjacent, and a vertex cover is a set of vertices that includes at least one endpoint of each edge in the graph.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] The vertex space of a graph is a vector space having a set of basis vectors corresponding with the graph's vertices.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] A graph is vertex-transitive if it has symmetries that map any vertex to any other vertex.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] In the context of graph enumeration and graph isomorphism it is important to distinguish between **labeled vertices** and **unlabeled vertices**.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] A labeled vertex is a vertex that is associated with extra information that enables it to be distinguished from other labeled vertices; two graphs can be considered isomorphic only if the correspondence between their vertices pairs up vertices with equal labels.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] An unlabeled vertex is one that can be substituted for any other vertex based only on its adjacencies in the graph and not based on any additional information.
[src:network-graph-viz/vertex-graph-theory] The vertex figure of a vertex in a polyhedron is analogous to the neighborhood of a vertex in a graph.
